I've read it Jenkin's column as well as in a few others.  The 2007 re-
signing was mostly done out of neccessity due to the Giants' inability
to attract any high level talent (Soriano and others).  If the Giants
signed Soriano last year, it's a pretty safe bet that they wouldn't
have signed Barry.  My guess is that the Sabean contract doesn't bode
well for another year with Bonds, either.

There's no guarantees that he won't get signed, but I'd say the odds
are looking slim based on what I've been reading as of late.  His
defense and base running are quickly becoming big liabilities.  His
plate appearances have also taken a drop in the second half, and
figuring out how to manage his late inning replacement or off day
replacement seems to have taken up an extra pitching spot on the
roster.  Unless the Giants could pick up a top tier bat to put behind
Bonds in the offseason, I doubt the Giants brass will extend an offer
to Bonds unless it's in the sub $10 million range.

