Bonds' base running isn't a big liability; it even isn't a small
liability.  I've seen Bonds race around the bases enough this year to
realize he still has plenty of speed on the base paths.

But there's no escaping the fact, because of his lack of range, that
Bonds has become a significant liability on the field, and unless the
Giants obtain a gold-glove quality centerfielder during the off-season
-- a big if -- it would be hard to justify starting Bonds in left field.

Unless Bonds is willing to play first base (which in the past he has
declined to do so) it will be hard to find a position for Bonds to field
without creating a big hole in the Giants defense.

That said, the Giants need more bats, not less, and Bonds will probably
still be a very high quality slugger next year.  So the Giants have a
big problem this off-season.  Unless the Giants can find a real
replacement for the offense Barry provides, it would be hard for the
Giants to justify letting him go.

If the Giants were going to suck again next year, I would rather watch
the Giants suck with Barry Bonds on the team than without him.

- Peter
