I agree that it would be more in keeping with tradition for Bonds to
develop a style that looks less apparently sluggish, even if it isn't
actually faster. But since I can remember Bonds has declined to bust
down the line on every routine play to take advantage of possible
defensive lapses. There's a reasonable argument in support of that: the
few additional times a year he might reach base just aren't worth the
risk of losing him for 15 games or more because of an injury. Even now
he's too valuable to the offense for that risk to pay off reliably.
Looking back, it might have been better for his team if George Brett,
for example, had played &quot;all out&quot; a little less and was out of action a
lot less.

Regarding Bonds as an example for younger players, I haven't seen
evidence that other Giants think they can emulate Bonds' disdain for
traditional hustle. Frandsen is the only one I can think of who has cost
the Giants a few outs by not running when he should have, but those were
apparently cases of brainlock, not Bondsishness. Bondsism. Bondsheit.
Whatever.

Among the problems the Giants have that are larger than lack of hustle
are 1) outfielders who reach too few flyballs because they take poor
routes to them, 2) baserunners who take too few extra bases because they
have ancient catcher's legs, even though they seldom or never catch, and
3) other than the good young pitchers and Davis when he's getting on
base, being terminally boring regardless of their degree of effort.

But although I don't think Bonds is the chief cause of any of the
Giants' key problems, it's clear that he's not the solution to any of
them either. There is something appealing about letting him go and
declaring the start of a new era, even if the same old sheriff is still
in charge. At least he wouldn't be able to hide behind the lame excuse
anymore that he was compelled to sign only upside-free players while
Bonds was still on the roster.
